  "text": "There are clear resonances and important differences. Both Ra and Buddhism point toward unity and the primacy of inner transformation: Ra summarizes the teaching as “all things are one,” with healing and realization arising when the mind/body/spirit recognizes that unity. This aligns with Buddhist aims of seeing through separation, reducing attachment, and cultivating compassion as a way out of suffering.\n\n\n\nWhere they diverge is in framework and emphasis. Ra frames moral/energetic orientation as polarity—service to others versus service to self—and places teachings in a cosmological scheme of densities, harvest, and chosen polarization. Buddhism does not use the polarity/harvest model; it centers on the Four Noble Truths, the Eightfold Path, non-self (anatta), and the Middle Way as the practical method to end suffering. Ra’s language about polarity and service reframes compassion as one pole of a cosmic choice rather than only a remedy for dukkha.\n\n\n\nPractically, both encourage meditation and ethical living. If you practice both, you might notice Buddhism’s strong emphasis on insight into impermanence and non-self complements Ra’s emphasis on loving service and polarity as directional choices for the soul. Each offers useful tools: Buddhism’s dispassionate inquiry helps loosen attachment, while Ra’s view invites deliberate polarization toward service as a long-term spiritual aim. Which approach feels more clarifying may depend on whether you prefer a soteriology grounded in insight and cessation (Buddhism) or a cosmic teleology of unity, polarity, and harvest (Ra).",
  "quotes": [
